I hate it when CEO's like this make up their own psychology rules about what works with hiring and employees.

 Basically these psychology rules end up being pseudo psychology. Giving employees a difficult or impossible task in their first day day so that they fail does NOT encourage creative thinking.

 Where does this guy get this information from? He is not a workplace psychologist, nor did he even research actual psychology.

 Discouraging people makes them feel like failures. According to actual behavior science, you increase desired behaviors by offering powerful positive reinforcement. 

Behavior researchers have found through actual research that punishment decreased desired behavior. 

Plus to be creative, you have to feel free and uninhibited. You have to feel inspired as well. 

This guy basically just revealed that he is just one of those typical narcissists playing king of the castle in his own delusional world, so narcissistic that he thinks he automatically has actual dominion over actual behavioral science.

 He represents toxic leadership. People need to feel fairly encouraged and supported to do well.

comment_text:
So many parents are confused as to why you chose to glamorize someone who continues to build and profit from a business that has devastated the lives of millions of teenage girls. Any parent—especially those raising daughters—who has witnessed the heartbreaking, catastrophic effects of social media understands the damage being done.

While I genuinely wish Evan and his family well, and he may be a kind person, the impact of his work is undeniable. The increase in mindlessness, aimlessness, depression, anxiety, and body dysmorphia among vulnerable children is heartbreaking—and it’s tragic to see these outcomes treated as collateral in the pursuit of success.

Celebrating him on your podcast feels like a slap in the face to those of us who are doing everything we can to help our daughters recover their health, their confidence, and their sense of self.

comment_text:
Video suggests "tomorrow" ruins your life by encouraging procrastination.
Argues "I'll do it tomorrow" delays action and kills momentum, preventing goal achievement.
Claims repeated use of "tomorrow" builds an avoidance habit, linked to resisting discomfort.
Promotes starting tasks today to develop discipline.
Concept is simple and relatable, connecting to common procrastination struggles.
Ties to self-help, focusing on mindset shifts for growth.
Lacks specific evidence, relying on anecdotal points.
Offers a practical tip: swap "tomorrow" for "now" to boost productivity.
Oversimplifies procrastination, which can stem from deeper issues like fear or overwhelm.
Works as motivational content but isn’t a full solution.
